{{Redirect|Healthy Kids|Australian program|Healthy Kids Association}} {{Infobox Organization |name = '''Action for Healthy Kids''' |image = |image_border = |size = 250px |caption = |map = |msize = |mcaption = |abbreviation = |motto = |formation = 2002 |extinction = |type = [[Youth organization]] |status = [[Non-profit organization]] |purpose = To engage diverse organizations, leaders and volunteers in actions that foster sound nutrition and good physical activity in children, youth and schools. |headquarters = Chicago, IL |location ={{flag|United States|civil}} |region_served = All 50 US states |membership = |language = |leader_title = CEO |leader_name = Rob Bisceglie |main_organ = |parent_organization = |affiliations = |num_staff = |num_volunteers = 100,000+<ref>[http://www.actionforhealthykids.org/about-us About Us.] Action for Healthy Kids. Retrieved 10/01/16.</ref> |budget = |website = [http://www.actionforhealthykids.org] Official website |remarks = }}
'''Action for Healthy Kids''' is a public-private partnership of more than 75 organizations<ref>Kupst, J.A. (2007) "Leveraging best practices from the field of community development to increase consumption of healthier foods and promote physical activity in southern New Jersey." Cornell University. p 39.</ref> dedicated to promoting school health.<ref>Lambdin, D. (2010) ''Fitness for Life: Elementary School Classroom Guide.'' Human Kinetics. p 39.</ref> Founded in 2002, the organization addresses the epidemic of overweight, sedentary, and undernourished youth by focusing on changes in schools to improve nutrition and increase physical activity.<ref>[http://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=11020 "Action for Healthy Kids"], Charity Navigator. Retrieved 7/7/10.</ref> Former [[U.S. Surgeon General]] [[David Satcher]] is the founding chair of the organization.<ref>[http://www.actionforhealthykids.org/about-us/board/david-satcher-bio.html "David Satcher Biography."] Action For Healthy Kids. Retrieved 7/7/10.</ref>
The organization has active volunteers in all 50 states and the District of Columbia.<ref>[http://www.kelloggcompany.com/social.aspx?id=58 "Children and Youth"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713142819/http://www.kelloggcompany.com/social.aspx?id=58 |date=July 13, 2011 }}, Kellogg Company. Retrieved 7/10/10.</ref> Their activities are supported by a variety of organizations, including the [[Kellogg Company]],<ref>[http://www.kelloggcompany.com/social.aspx?id=58 "Children and Youth"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713142819/http://www.kelloggcompany.com/social.aspx?id=58 |date=July 13, 2011 }}, Kellogg Company. Retrieved 7/10/10.</ref> the [[National Dairy Council]], and [[General Mills]].<ref>7/7/10. [http://www.marketwatch.com/story/national-dairy-councilr-and-general-mills-foodservice-to-award-k-12-schools-100000-in-grants-to-build-breakfast-programs-2010-07-07?reflink=MW_news_stmp "National Dairy Council and General Mills Foodservice to Award K-12 Schools $100,000 in Grants to Build Breakfast Programs"] MarketWatch.com. Retrieved 7/10/10.</ref> Working with Kellogg, the organization provided financial support to schools to support National School Breakfast Week. They are partners with the National Dairy Council and the [[National Football League]] in a program called "Fuel Up To Play 60."<ref>7/7/10. [http://www.sacbee.com/2010/07/07/2875205/cleveland-browns-own-mohamed-massaquoi.html "Cleveland Browns' Own Mohamed Massaquoi Joins Milk Mustache Mobile Tour to Celebrate Family Dinner,"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100712070725/http://www.sacbee.com/2010/07/07/2875205/cleveland-browns-own-mohamed-massaquoi.html |date=July 12, 2010 }} ''The Sacramento Bee.'' Retrieved 7/10/10.</ref>
