{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Sara Howard | honorific_suffix = FRCSLT | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | occupation = {{plainlist| * Speech Therapist }} | awards = | alma_mater = [[University of Sheffield]] | thesis_year = | discipline = | sub_discipline = | workplaces = {{plainlist| * University of Sheffield }} }}
'''Sara Howard''' FRCSLT is a British [[Speech Therapist|speech therapist]] and Professor Emerita of Clinical Phonetics at the [[University of Sheffield]].<ref name='UoS'>{{cite web |url=https://www.sheffield.ac.uk/hcs/staff/howard |title=Professor Sara Howard|publisher=University of Sheffield |accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>
==Career== Howard earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in English and an [[Master of Arts|MA]] in Linguistics at the [[University of Leeds]] before receiving a [[BSc]] in Speech & Language Therapy at [[Leeds Metropolitan University]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in Clinical Phonetics at the University of Sheffield. She works in the area of the phonetics/phonology interface in developmental speech impairments (especially cleft lip and palate).<ref name='UoS' />
Between 2010 and 2012 Howard completed an [[Economic and Social Research Council|ESRC Research Fellowship]] on "Connected speech and word juncture in typical and atypical speech development".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.researchcatalogue.esrc.ac.uk/grants/RES-070-27-0024/read |title=Connected speech and word juncture in typical and atypical speech development |publisher=ESRC |accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>
Howard was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal College of Speech and Language Therapists]] in 2015,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rcslt.org/honours_roll_call_1945-2016 |title=RCSLT Honours Roll Call |publisher=Royal College of Speech and Lanuage Therapists |accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> and as a life member of the [[International Clinical Phonetics and Linguistics Association]] in 2016 of which she was president from 2006 to 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icpla.info/about |title=About the ICPLA |publisher=ICPLA |accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>
==Select publications== *Howard, S. J. 2013. 'A phonetic investigation of single word versus connected speech production in children with persisting speech difficulties relating to cleft palate'. ''Cleft Palate – Craniofacial Journal'', 50(2): 207-223. *Howard, S. J. & Lohmander, A. (eds) 2011. ''Cleft Palate Speech: Assessment and Intervention''. Chichester: Wiley-Blackwell. *Howard, S. J. & Heselwood, B. C. 2011. 'Instrumental and perceptual phonetic analysis: The case for two-tier transcriptions'. ''Clinical Linguistics & Phonetics'', 25(11-12), 940-948. *Ball, M. J., Perkins, M. R., Mueller, N, & Howard, S. J. (eds) 2008. ''The Handbook of Clinical Linguistics''. Oxford: Blackwell. *Howard, S. J. 2007. 'The interplay between articulation and prosody in children with impaired speech: observations from electropalatography and perceptual analysis'. ''Advances in Speech-Language Pathology'', 9(1), 20-35.
