{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} {{Infobox recurring event | name = World Breastfeeding Week | native_name = | logo = [[File:World Breastfeeding Week Logo.jpg]] | logo_caption = World Breastfeeding Week 2009 Logo | imagesize = frameless | caption = World Breastfeeding Week 2009 Logo | date = | begins = 1 August | ends = 7 August | frequency = Yearly | location = Worldwide | years_active = {{age|1991|1|8}} | first = 1991 | last = | participants = Governments, Organization, Individuals | genre = | budget = | patron = | website = [http://worldbreastfeedingweek.org/ Official Homepage] | footnotes = In the Support of [[Breastfeeding]] }} {{See also|World Alliance for Breastfeeding Action}} '''World Breastfeeding Week''' ('''WBW''') is an annual celebration which is being held every year from 1 to 7 August in more than 120 countries. According to the 26 August data of ''WBW'' website{{r|WorldMap}}, 540 events have been held worldwide by more than 79 countries with 488 organizations and 406,620 participants for the ''World Breastfeeding Week 2010''.{{r|Canada|Journal17|France|WBWinfo}} See [http://worldbreastfeedingweek.org/pledges.htm WBW pledges] for the complete list.
Being organized by [[World Alliance for Breastfeeding Action|WABA]], [[World Health Organization|WHO]] and [[UNICEF]], ''WBW'' came up with the goal to promote [[Breastfeeding#Exclusive breastfeeding|exclusive breastfeeding]] for the first six months of life which yields tremendous health benefits, providing critical [[nutrient]]s, protection from deadly [[disease]]s such as [[pneumonia]] and fostering growth and development for the first time in 1991.{{r|LLLI}}
==History== World Breastfeeding Week was first celebrated in 1992 by [[World Alliance for Breastfeeding Action]] (WABA) and is now observed in over 120 [[countries]] by [[UNICEF]]{{r|UNICEF}}, [[World Health Organization|WHO]]{{r|WHO}} and their partners including individuals, organizations, and governments. WABA itself have been formed on 14 February 1991{{r|Fdate}} with the goal to re-establish a global breastfeeding culture and provide support for [[breastfeeding]] everywhere.{{r|AllSands}}
The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and the [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] (AAP) emphasize the value of breastfeeding for mothers as well as children. Both recommend exclusive breastfeeding for the first six months of life and then supplemented breastfeeding for at least one year and up to two years or more.{{r|WHO2003|Gartner_2005}} WBW commemorates the [[Innocenti Declaration]] made by WHO and UNICEF in August 1990 to protect and support breastfeeding.{{r|WHO}}
